144	  <main class="wrap">
145	    <section id="what">
146	      <h2>What Scrum is</h2>
147	      <p>Scrum is a lightweight framework that helps teams deliver value through iterative work, frequent inspection, and adaptation. It defines a small set of accountabilities, events, and artifacts — and leaves the details of how the work gets done to the team.</p>
148	    </section>
149	
150	    <section id="when">
151	      <h2>When it helps</h2>
152	      <p>Scrum fits complex problems where requirements and solutions are uncertain and need to be discovered through delivery. It helps when a team needs a steady cadence to ship something useful, learn from it, and adjust — rather than committing up front to a fixed plan.</p>
153	    </section>
154	
155	    <section id="roles">
156	      <h2>Roles (accountabilities)</h2>
157	      <p class="lede">A Scrum Team has three accountabilities — together they own delivering value each Sprint.</p>
158	      <div class="grid">
159	        <article class="card">
160	          <h3>Product Owner</h3>
161	          <p>Accountable for maximizing the value of the product by managing the Product Backlog.</p>
162	        </article>
163	        <article class="card">
164	          <h3>Scrum Master</h3>
165	          <p>Accountable for the team's effectiveness and for establishing Scrum as defined in the Scrum Guide.</p>
166	        </article>
167	        <article class="card">
168	          <h3>Developers</h3>
169	          <p>Accountable for creating a usable Increment that meets the Definition of Done every Sprint.</p>
170	        </article>
171	      </div>
172	    </section>
173	
174	    <section id="events">
175	      <h2>Events</h2>
176	      <p class="lede">Five time-boxed events create regularity and remove the need for other meetings.</p>
177	      <div class="grid">
178	        <article class="card">
179	          <h3>Sprint</h3>
180	          <p>A fixed, time-boxed container (one month or less) inside which all the other Scrum events happen and an Increment is created.</p>
181	        </article>
182	        <article class="card">
183	          <h3>Sprint Planning</h3>
184	          <p>Initiates the Sprint by defining why it is valuable, what can be done, and how the chosen work will get done.</p>
185	        </article>
186	        <article class="card">
187	          <h3>Daily Scrum</h3>
188	          <p>A 15-minute event for Developers to inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapt the plan for the next day.</p>
189	        </article>
190	        <article class="card">
191	          <h3>Sprint Review</h3>
192	          <p>Inspects the outcome of the Sprint with stakeholders and determines future adaptations to the Product Backlog.</p>
193	        </article>
194	        <article class="card">
195	          <h3>Sprint Retrospective</h3>
196	          <p>Closes the Sprint by planning ways to increase quality and effectiveness in how the team works together.</p>
197	        </article>
198	      </div>
199	    </section>
200	
201	    <section id="artifacts">
202	      <h2>Artifacts</h2>
203	      <p class="lede">Each artifact represents work or value, and each has a commitment that gives it focus.</p>
204	      <div class="grid">
205	        <article class="card">
206	          <h3>Product Backlog</h3>
207	          <p>An ordered list of what is needed to improve the product. Its commitment is the Product Goal.</p>
208	        </article>
209	        <article class="card">
210	          <h3>Sprint Backlog</h3>
211	          <p>The plan by and for the Developers — the Sprint Goal, the selected Product Backlog items, and how to deliver them.</p>
212	        </article>
213	        <article class="card">
214	          <h3>Increment</h3>
215	          <p>A concrete step toward the Product Goal. Each Increment is additive to all prior Increments and must be usable.</p>
216	        </article>
217	        <article class="card">
218	          <h3>Definition of Done</h3>
219	          <p>The shared standard of quality an Increment must meet to be considered complete and releasable.</p>
220	        </article>
221	      </div>
222	    </section>
223	
224	    <section id="sprint">
225	      <h2>The Sprint: a time-boxed container</h2>
226	      <p>The Sprint is the heartbeat of Scrum. It is a fixed-length cycle, one month or less, during which the team turns ideas into a usable Increment. Sprint Planning opens it, the Daily Scrum keeps it on track, and the Sprint Review and Retrospective close it — same length, same rhythm, every time.</p>
